   <h1>Solving the Quadratic Equation</h1>
   <p>A <b>quadratic equation</b> is a polynomial equation of the second degree, having 
   the general form:</p>

   <p id="eq1">
       
           
   <m:mrow>
     <m:mrow>
       <m:mn>a</m:mn>
       <m:msup>
         <m:mi>x</m:mi>
         <m:mn>2</m:mn>
       </m:msup>
       <m:mo>+</m:mo>
       <m:mrow>
         <m:mn>b</m:mn>
         <m:mi>x</m:mi>
       </m:mrow>
       <m:mo>+</m:mo>
       <m:mn>c</m:mn>
     </m:mrow>
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
     <m:mn>0</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>   
           


   </p>

   <p>The letters a, b and c are called coefficients: a is the coefficient of 
   <i>x</i><sup>2</sup>, b is the coefficient of <i>x</i>, and c is the constant coefficient.
   A quadratic equation has two complex roots (i.e., solutions for the unknown term <i>x</i>.) 
   In some cases, these roots can have the same value. The roots can also belong to the realm 
   of <b>complex numbers</b>. The values of the roots can be computed using the <b>quadratic 
   formula</b> as shown below:</p>

   <p id="eq2">

       
   <m:mrow>
     <m:mi>x</m:mi>
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
     <m:mfrac>
        <m:mrow>
         <m:mrow>
           <m:mo>-</m:mo>
           <m:mi>b</m:mi>
         </m:mrow>
         <m:mo>&#177;</m:mo>
         <m:msqrt>
           <m:mrow>
             <m:msup>
               <m:mi>b</m:mi>
               <m:mn>2</m:mn>
             </m:msup>
             <m:mo>-</m:mo>
             <m:mrow>
               <m:mn>4</m:mn>
               <m:mi>a</m:mi>
               <m:mi>c</m:mi>
             </m:mrow>
           </m:mrow>
         </m:msqrt>
       </m:mrow>
       <m:mrow>
         <m:mn>2</m:mn>
         <m:mi>a</m:mi>
       </m:mrow>
     </m:mfrac>
   </m:mrow>

   </p>

    <p>For example, the roots of the quadratic equation</p>
    
   
   <p id="eq3">

   <m:mrow>
     <m:mrow>
       <m:mn>2</m:mn>
       <m:msup>
         <m:mi>x</m:mi>
         <m:mn>2</m:mn>
       </m:msup>
       <m:mo>-</m:mo>
       <m:mrow>
         <m:mn>14</m:mn>
         <m:mi>x</m:mi>
       </m:mrow>
       <m:mo>+</m:mo>
       <m:mn>20</m:mn>
     </m:mrow>
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
     <m:mn>0</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>       
       
   </p>



   <p>can be determined by first substituting 2 for a, -14 for b, and 20 for c</p>

   <p id="eq4">
       
 
   <m:mrow>
     <m:mi>x</m:mi>
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
     <m:mfrac>
        <m:mrow>
         <m:mrow>
           <m:mi>14</m:mi>
         </m:mrow>
         <m:mo>&#177;</m:mo>
         <m:msqrt>
           <m:mrow>
               
             <m:msup>
               <m:mi>(-14)</m:mi>
               <sup>
                   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
               </sup>
               
             </m:msup>
              <m:mo>-</m:mo>
            <m:mrow>
               <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                   <m:mo></m:mo>
               <m:mi>(2)</m:mi>
               <m:mo>(20)</m:mo>
             </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
         </m:msqrt>
       </m:mrow>
       <m:mrow>
         <m:mn>2</m:mn>
         <m:mo></m:mo>
         <m:mi>(2)</m:mi>
       </m:mrow>
     </m:mfrac>
   </m:mrow>

   </p>

   <p>and then solving the expression, which gives the roots of the equation as either <i>x</i> = 5 or <i>x</i> = 2.</p>

